### 19. Context

Created `AuthContext` and `AuthProvider` (structure + concept).

Without Context: 
<App>
  <Login user={user} setUser={setUser} />
</App>

<Login user={user} setUser={setUser} />
  â””â”€â”€ <Header user={user} />
       â””â”€â”€ <Profile user={user} />

Data is passed:
App â†’ Login â†’ Header â†’ Profile
Even if intermediate components donâ€™t care.

This becomes messy.

-----

With Context:

<AuthProvider>
  <App />
</AuthProvider>

<App>
  <Login />
</App>

<Login />
  â””â”€â”€ <Header />
       â””â”€â”€ <Profile />   â† consumes user directly

user is NOT passed as props
Profile reads it directly from Context
Data Flow: 
AuthProvider (user state lives here)
        â†“
Context
        â†“
Profile (reads user)


### 20. Refs (conceptual exposure)

You discussed DOM access vs React control (even though refs not coded yet).

State   â†’ â€œReact, re-render when this changes.â€
Effect  â†’ â€œReact, run this side-effect after render.â€
Ref     â†’ â€œReact, remember this without re-rendering.â€
Memo    â†’ â€œReact, skip re-render if props didnâ€™t change.â€
Context â†’ â€œReact, make this data globally available without prop drilling.â€
Props   â†’ â€œReact, pass data from parent to child.â€


